<h2>The rise and fall of web software buttons</h2>

<p>
It's hard to tell when those buttons completely fell out of fashion, but I think it was
in the first few years of the web 2.0 era. One possible reason is that at the time when large
scale attacks became common, revealing anything about your software stack seemed like a bad idea,
and people started reconfiguring their servers to hide anything that could help attackers find
an attack vector.
</p>
<p>
If we assume that promoting open source software was one of the most important reasons,
perhaps the fact that the web backend standardized on open source software also played a role,
there wasn't so much need for advocacy anymore.
</p>
<p>
Or maybe it's just changing fashions. Regardless, we can hardly see those buttons on new
websites, for better or worse, and they remain a characteristic feature of a past era.
</p>

